@startuml object-history-stack
'' ============================================================================
'' PlantUML over Mermaid because: this illustrates the EVOLUTION of one mutable
'' value ({:stack :idx}) across a sequence of operations, with the forward
'' branch being TRUNCATED on a divergent navigation. PlantUML objects let each
'' snapshot be a typed record with the active index highlighted; ordered arrows
'' between snapshots narrate the Command-pattern transitions. Mermaid lacks
'' record objects with per-field highlighting and snapshot-to-snapshot arrows.
'' ============================================================================
!include _vv-theme.iuml

title :ui/history evolution — A → B → C → back → D truncates the forward branch

'' Each object is one snapshot of {:stack [...] :idx n}. The bracketed «idx»
'' marks the entry the current active-path points at.

object "S0 · initial" as S0 #7590DB {
  stack = []
  idx   = -1
  active = (none)
}

object "S1 · nav A" as S1 #7590DB {
  stack = [ **A«0»** ]
  idx   = 0
  active = A
}

object "S2 · nav B" as S2 #7590DB {
  stack = [ A, **B«1»** ]
  idx   = 1
  active = B
}

object "S3 · nav C" as S3 #7590DB {
  stack = [ A, B, **C«2»** ]
  idx   = 2
  active = C
}

object "S4 · back" as S4 #4F97D7 {
  stack = [ A, **B«1»**, C ]
  idx   = 1
  active = B
  --
  (C retained;\n idx moved left)
}

object "S5 · nav D (divergent)" as S5 #E0211D {
  stack = [ A, B, **D«2»** ]
  idx   = 2
  active = D
  --
  (forward branch C\n **truncated**)
}

S0 -[#A45BAD,thickness=2]-> S1 : nav-to A\nrecord-nav: conj A
S1 -[#A45BAD,thickness=2]-> S2 : nav-to B\nrecord-nav: conj B
S2 -[#A45BAD,thickness=2]-> S3 : nav-to C\nrecord-nav: conj C
S3 -[#4F97D7,thickness=2]-> S4 : :history/back\nidx ← idx−1   (stack unchanged)
S4 -[#E0211D,thickness=2]-> S5 : nav-to D\nrecord-nav truncates:\nstack' ≔ (conj (vec (take (inc idx) stack)) D)\n      = (conj [A B] D)

note bottom of S5
  **record-nav** keeps only `take (inc idx)` of the old stack before appending
  the new path, then sets `idx ≔ (dec (count stack'))`. This is exactly the
  browser-history rule: navigating after a Back **discards** the forward branch.
  Navigating to the path you are already on is a no-op (no duplicate entry).
end note

legend right
  |= color |= concept |
  | <#7590DB> | app-db ephemeral UI state (a history snapshot) |
  | <#A45BAD> | a forward navigation (record-nav appends) |
  | <#4F97D7> | back/forward move (idx slides, stack frozen) |
  | <#E0211D> | divergent nav — forward branch truncated |
endlegend
@enduml
